[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[FEN "r2qrbk1/1b1n1pp1/p2p3p/1ppP4/Pn2P3/5N1P/1P1N1PP1/RBBQR1K1 w - - 1 17"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Revisiting Kasparov's coordination"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/XOSMGTBA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2qrbk1/1b1n1pp1/p2p3p/1ppP4/Pn2P3/5N1P/1P1N1PP1/RBBQR1K1 w - - 1 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We saw this famous Kasparov - Karpov game from 1990 in the last study on talking to your pieces ( https://lichess.org/study/kjBSgqoA/WOJiXkSD ), but now let's revisit this game through the lens of "pawns aren't people."

As before, we have arrived at a Benoni structure, although the opening was originally from the Zaitsev variation of the Ruy Lopez. }
17. Ra3! { Kasparov coordinates his heavy pieces, ready for the center to come under heavy fire. } 17... f5!? { A contentious move - striking at the center is logical, but this weakens the kingside a bit and white's pieces are well-placed for a kingside attack as we shall see.
Immediately, we can see that Karpov is arguing on behalf of pawns being relevant (white's center is sure to collapse), while Kasparov is arguing against them mattering (if the center opens, white's pieces are better coordinated to attack on the kingside). } 18. Rae3 { Already, black can win the d5 pawn. But it comes at the cost of ripping open the position for white's well-coordinated pieces! } 18... Nf6 (18... fxe4?! 19. Nxe4 Nxd5 20. R3e2 $14 { In particular, white's bishop pair has become a menace! } { [%cal Bb1h7,Bc1h6,Be1e8] }) 19. Nh2! { The whole point of this mysterious move is to give white's rook access to the g3 square just in case it gets attacked by black's knight. A true example of talking to your pieces to find a nice prophylactic idea. } 19... Kh8 (19... fxe4? { Now winning a pawn proves fatal for black. } 20. Nxe4 Nfxd5 21. Rg3! $16 { Pawns aren't people! In exchange for the d5 pawn, every single white piece is active, and attacking white's king. Black is not long for this world. } { [%cal Bg3g8,Bc1h6,Bb1h7,Bd1h5] }) 20. b3! { Activating the DSB along the a1-h8 diagonal. } 20... bxa4 21. bxa4 c4?! { Played just to give black's b4 knight the d3 square to shut out white's LSB. However, this move doesn't address the desires of the a8 rook or b7 bishop. } (21... Rb8! 22. Bb2 Ba8! $14 { This is perhaps the best way to coordinate black's pieces - already black has threats against the loose bishops on the b file. Still, white retains excellent attacking potential on the kingside. }) 22. Bb2 { White's army is glaring menacingly at black's king. Karpov cracks and decides that if he's going to suffer, it's best to suffer while up a pawn. } 22... fxe4 23. Nxe4 Nfxd5 24. Rg3 $16 { At least black is up a pawn. But pawns aren't people!
In exchange for that pawn, every single white piece has built up potential for a kingside attack. Note how powerful the two bishops are, raking across the board, how the queen is ready to jump in to h5 at a moment's notice, and how both knights are ready to sacrifice themselves (either on g5 or h6).
From this position, Kasparov went on to win a crushing game: https://lichess.org/5WymoNVe#47 } { [%cal Bb2h8,Bb1h7,Bd1h5,Bg3g7] } *


