[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.03.28"]
[UTCTime "17:31:35"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Our position looks promising since white's bishop pair is currently under control. But how to make progress? Which side of the board should we be playing? }
1... e4! (1... a3!? { This move is reasonable too, but it is only good if our follow-up is the same as what was played in the game. } 2. b3 e4! $17) (1... Qe7 $15 { Sensible development, but we have a real pawns aren't people move available to us that's much stronger. }) (1... Kg7? $10 { The king is not safer on this square. }) (1... Rb8? $16 { Oh no, our a pawn! }) (1... f4? $10 { Giving up control over the e4 square is not a good way to begin an attack. After Qe4, black is the one under pressure. }) (1... g5? $18 { Oh no, our f5 pawn! }) 2. Bxf6 (2. f4? Bxc3 3. bxc3 $17 { The passed pawn on e4 is still impressive. }) (2. fxe4!? Bxc3 3. bxc3 f4! $17 { The same idea is strong here too. }) 2... Qxf6 (2... Rxf6 $15 { Not bad, but the rook gets in the way of our queen's route to the kingside dark squares. Remember to talk to all of your pieces! }) (2... Nxf6?! $10 { The wrong recapture. Our knight from f6 is not able to reach the more important outpost: e5. Remember to talk to all of your pieces! }) (2... exf3?? { Oops. Qe6+ wins our queen! } 3. Qe6+ $18) 3. fxe4 f4! { The point of our sequence! Sacrificing the potential passed pawn is a thematic way to break through. Remember: pawns aren't people. Now the e5 square is available for the knight, and in fact the e4 pawn is a traitor to white's pieces. } (3... fxe4?? $18 { Oh no, our queen! }) (3... Qe5?! $15 { This keeps the e pawn, but the knight would prefer to land on this square. }) (3... Qxb2?! { A "pawns are people" move. This pawn will always be weak, and after exf5 white's bishop breathes fire towards our newly weakened king. }) (3... Ne5? $16 { The right idea, but let's not give white the chance to play exf5 and open up their light squared bishop. }) *


