[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 6: Avoiding catastrophe"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/fDHakgRZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2p3b1/3p3p/p1pPp1p1/2P5/5PN1/PP4PP/1R3RK1 b - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This position is a typical endgame arising from the King's Indian Defense. Black to move - good luck! }
26... e4! $10 { That's absolutely correct! All other moves on the board allow Ne4, when the amazing knight blockades the e5 pawn and leaves us with a terrible bishop.
Now that you know that pawns aren't people, it's easy to see that our e pawn was a traitor to our bishop. With the e5 pawn on the board, we would have to be groveling for a draw. Without the e5 pawn on the board, we actually have good chances of outplaying white from this position, simply because the bishop is such a monster on e5 or d4!
In the game, Radjabov masterfully outplayed his opponent from this position: https://lichess.org/QP3qJvrc#52 } *


[Event "1990 Soviet Army Championship"]
[Date "1990"]
[White "Alexander Graf"]
[Black "Alexander Semeniuk"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "IM"]
[BlackTitle "IM"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 7: Making progress"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/4NhRWsFD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "4k3/1R6/5K1p/p4P2/6P1/8/4r3/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ With a strongly placed king and rook, we're clearly close to winning this endgame. Can you find the final breakthrough? }
1. g5! (1. Kg7?? { This idea to try and make progress makes sense, but fails to Rg2! when the g pawn is hanging with check. } 1... Rg2 $10) (1. Rb8+?! { Probably not a good idea. Once the king escapes from the back rank, it's hard to imagine you're winning unless you can queen the f pawn immediately. Sadly, you can't because Kd7 Kf7?? Re4! draws the game. } 1... Kd7 2. Kf7?? Re4! 3. f6 Rxg4 4. Kf8 a4 5. f7 a3 $10 { Black will sacrifice the rook for the f pawn and draw the game. }) (1. Ra7!? $18 { This move doesn't throw anything away, so it's also playable. But if you were hoping to win the a pawn, you're still operating under the delusion that pawns are people when they're not! }) 1... hxg5 { Black couldn't allow you to play g6, when the two connected passed pawns would instantly win the game. Was the point of your last move to trade pawns? } 2. Kg7! (2. Kxg5?? { Pawns aren't people! We want our king safe from checks on the g file, not to simply recapture this pawn! }) (2. Kg6 $18 { While this move also wins, there's a more active square for your king instead. }) 2... Rf2 { Exactly! Keep it up! } (2... Re7+ 3. Rxe7+ Kxe7 4. f6+ $18 { [%cal Gf6f8] }) 3. f6! g4 4. f7+! Kd8 5. f8=Q+ Rxf8 6. Kxf8 $18 { Great find! By using black's g pawn as shelter, you were able to get your king up in the endgame as much as possible. Once you're up a rook, picking off black's remaining two pawns is easy. } (6. Rb8+ $18 { Also playable. Just recapture with the king for the solution. }) *


