[White "Jan Foltys"]
[Black "Carlos Skalicka"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 8: Queenside play"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/Ff6esIIM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1rr3k1/5ppp/1n2pb2/p1p5/P7/1PP1BP2/1NK3PP/3R3R w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This position appears at first sight to be reasonably equal. Yet this exercise is quite difficult - can you squeeze blood out of a stone to eke out an advantage here? }
1. Nc4! (1. c4?? { Oh no! After Bxb2, your c and a pawns are hanging! } 1... Bxb2! 2. Kxb2 Nxc4+ $19) 1... Nxc4 (1... Nd5!? { In actual fact, black should probably avoid the temptation to damage white's pawn structure. } 2. Rd3 $16) 2. bxc4 Rb6 { Your queenside pawn structure has been destroyed. Was there any benefit to allowing the knight trade? } 3. Rb1 Rcb8? { That's right. "Every pawn lost is a file gained." In this case, your double isolated c pawns are fantastic at controlling all of the entrance squares for black's rooks on the b file, and giving you an open file to use yourself! } (3... Rbc6!? { Played in the game. } 4. Rhd1 $16 { But it should be clear that black has nothing positive to say about his position here. Every black piece is saddened by their purely defensive duties. }) 4. Rb5! $18 { Nice job! The rook stands amazingly on b5, from where it threatens both pawns. Moreover, if it is captured, cxb5 simply kills black's rook and gives us a connected passed pawn on b5. Black is completely lost here. } (4. Bxc5!? { This is also a good move, but you have to see that after the trade of rooks, you're not actually winning a pawn because c3 is falling. There's much cleaner in this position instead. } 4... Rxb1! 5. Rxb1 Rxb1 6. Kxb1 Bxc3 7. Kc2 Be1 $18 { [%cal Gc4c8] }) *


[Event "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II: Pawns are people!"]
[Date "2024.03.28"]
[White "Ay1010"]
[Black "NoseKnowsAll"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Pawns are people!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/8bSHUD23"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1rbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/4p3/8/QnpP4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 6 12"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.03.28"]
[UTCTime "17:31:35"]

{ It's important to understand both when a rule/principle is true, but also when it is not. While sacrificing a pawn for activity is typically correct in dynamic positions, you have to actually achieve something dynamic in exchange for your pawn. }
12... Bd7?! { In this game, I decided to (wrongly) sacrifice the a pawn in order to activate all of my pieces. } (12... Rb6! { Correct. Now the a pawn cannot be captured without allowing a perpetual on white's queen. Best play is probably: } 13. a3 (13. Qxa7?! Ra6 14. Qb8 Rb6 15. Qa7 Ra6 $10 { The queen cannot escape the rook. }) 13... Ra6 14. Qd1 Nc6 $14 { where black has kicked back white's queen and almost equalized. }) 13. Qxa7 Rb6?! { I tried to argue that pawns aren't people. In exchange for the pawn, I thought I was trapping the queen in Siberia and getting on with play in the center. } 14. Bf4! { But my opponent shows me the error of my ways! In actual fact, the queen on a7 is well-placed and coordinating well with both bishops. My c pawn is an accessible target, and now I have to spend tempi defending. White is simply up a pawn for nothing. } 14... Bd6 15. Qxb6! { Oops! So much for the queen being offsides! } 15... cxb6 16. Bxd6 Nc6 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 $16 { White has way too much material for the queen here, and probably would have converted if not for later errors under time pressure. } { Ay1010 - NoseKnowsAll, 0-1, -, https://lichess.org/Fcl6tfGK } *


[Event "Tata Steel Chess 2023 Masters"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee, Netherlands"]
[Date "2023.01.29"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Arjun Erigaisi"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteElo "2722"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2859"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Board "3"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Pawns are people!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/Ul1sLzIf"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2q3k1/2pbbn2/1p1p1n2/1N1Pp1p1/1PP1PpP1/2NQ1P2/6B1/1KB5 b - - 0 34"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here's one more exception to the rule. In this position, Magnus Carlsen uncorks a flashy sequence with the argument that pawns ARE people. }
34... Nxg4! 35. fxg4 Bxg4 { Carlsen's argument is that the two connected passed pawns on the f and g file control so much space and are so close to queening that they are in fact worth a piece. } 36. Bf3 Bh3 37. Bh5 g4 { Indeed, Carlsen is correct - the pawns are worth a piece. Try coordinating your pieces as white in a way that prevents those pawns from queening. Erigaisi couldn't! } 38. Ne2 Bf1 39. Qd1 Bg2 40. Bg6 Ng5 { Note how patient Carlsen is with pushing his pawns. While the connected passed pawns are his main asset in the position, he's quite comfortable maneuvering his pieces to their optimal squares first. He wants to ensure that when he does push the pawns, he won't be leaving behind holes that white can pounce on. Even after sacrificing a piece, Carlsen shows astute understanding that pawns aren't people. } 41. Nbc3 Bf3 42. Qf1 Kg7 43. Bf5 Qh8 { With the threat of g3-g2-g1 hanging over his head, Erigaisi tries to bail out by sacrificing back the piece for two pawns. } 44. Nxf4?! exf4 45. Bxf4 Bf6 $17 { The problem for white: black's passed g pawn is much stronger than white's backwards e pawn, and every black piece is more active than the white counterpart.
PRO TIP: A pawn phalanx approaching the 8th rank can sometimes be worth a piece. If you're in such an imbalanced position playing with the piece, then you have to ensure your pieces are as active as possible! If you're in such an imbalanced position playing with the pawns, then you have to keep your opponent's pieces as passive as possible and slowly creep forward with the pawns. } *


[Event "36th ECC Open 2021"]
[Date "2021.09.23"]
[Round "6.1"]
[White "Kirill Alekseenko"]
[Black "Jaime Santos Latasa"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2693"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2627"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Alekseenko's \"pawns aren't people\" masterpiece"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/mzukOd51"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1r5r/2qbkpp1/p2pp3/1p4Rn/3QP3/2N2P2/PPP4P/1K1R1B2 w - - 2 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We finish this study with an impressive game showcasing Alekseenko's understanding that pawns aren't people.

In this position, Alekseenko already has a strong position because Santos Latasa's king is vulnerable in the center. Here, white plays a crushing sacrifice, embracing the "pawns aren't people" mentality. }
17. e5! { Blowing open the center while black is unable to get his king to safety. } 17... dxe5 (17... d5?? { The move black wanted to make simply fails tactically. } 18. Qh4! $18 { The knight is hit twice, and hanging with discovered check. Black loses a piece. }) 18. Qb4+! { In exchange for the sacrificed pawn, Alekseenko has opened the e4 square for the knight, the d file for the rook, and the a3-f8 diagonal for the queen. Altogether that's an excellent trade for the life of one measly pawn. } 18... Ke8 19. Ne4! { White uses another advantage of his "pawns aren't people" sacrifice - the e4 square has been cleared for the knight. Nd6+ is unstoppable, further harassing the black king. } 19... a5!? { Poking the queen takes the sting out of Nd6+, but Alekseenko finds a way to continue fighting for the initiative. } (19... Rb6!? 20. Nd6+ Rxd6 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 $18 { Black can always sacrifice the exchange and try to bail out into this endgame. But the a and e pawns are both hanging, so this is a clear exchange up for white, and white is winning. }) 20. Nd6+ Kf8! { Black's idea behind a5. There is no scary discovered check! } 21. Qh4! { Hitting the pinned knight gains a tempo for white. Rxe5 is coming next to restore material equality and keep the initiative. } (21. Nxb5+? axb4 22. Nxc7 $10 { Black's point. }) 21... Qd8? { Too fancy. Now Alekseenko shows the whole world that he has mastered the "pawns aren't people" mentality. } (21... g6!? 22. Rxe5 $16 { White restores material equality, but all of white's pieces are attacking something of black's, while each of black's pieces are hoping to defend. Therefore, black is clearly worse. }) 22. f4!! { Opening up more lines for white's pieces - in particular the f1 bishop.
PRO TIP: Talking to your pieces combines with embracing the fact that pawns aren't people. Pawns are subservient to the wants and desires of the pieces.
Once you embrace that fact, you will play dynamic moves like this with full confidence that they are correct since this move brings white's bishop's dreams to fruition. } 22... Kg8?! { Black defends the rook so now the knight is apparently unpinned. } (22... exf4?! { Black can't even afford the tempo to capture this offered f pawn. } 23. Be2! g6 24. Bxh5 gxh5 (24... Rxh5?! 25. Rxh5 Qxh4 26. Rxh4 $18 { White emerges a rook up. }) 25. Qxf4 $18 { White's ferocious attack continues, now on the newly opened f file. }) (22... Nxf4?? 23. Qxh8+ $18 { Don't forget the knight is pinned! }) 23. Be2! { Just as Morphy taught us, Alekseenko brings his last piece into the game now that extra lines have been opened up by the previous pawn sacrifices. } 23... Be8 { Black admits defeat and simply allows the knight to be captured. There was no way to save the knight. } (23... Nf6?! { Moving the knight doesn't work because white has the winning tactic: } 24. Qxh8+! Kxh8 25. Nxf7+ Kg8 26. Nxd8 Rxd8 27. fxe5 $18 { White emerges up an exchange and pawn. }) (23... g6?! { Unfortunately for black, the g pawn is pinned. White simply wins a piece here too. } 24. Bxh5 $18) 24. Nxe8 Qxe8 25. Rxh5 Rxh5 26. Bxh5 $18 { Alekseenko, K. - Santos Latasa, J., 1-0, 36th ECC Open 2021, https://lichess.org/NajhFgaY } { Down a full piece, black resigned. } 1-0


